 for bestpractices and # Audit Export & Artifact Generation

## Overview
You will build a comprehensive feature set to export auditable artifacts for Investor Perception Index (IPI) calculations. The system will generate signed, exportable artifacts in JSON and PDF (human-readable) that reference raw payloads, include event lists, weighting parameters, and calculation inputs used for a given IPI view. It must support access control, integrity signing via a server-side key (KMS/HSM), and retention metadata for audit trails. The UI comprises a Company View (IPI Detail) and a Drilldown view (“Why did this move?”) with replayable narrative event timelines and raw payload visibility.

## Components to Build
1) Audit Export & Artifact Generator Service
- Responsibilities:
  - Assemble artifact payloads for a given IPI view (company, time window, narrative set).
  - Include: selected NarrativeEvents with raw payload IDs, exact inputs used for IPI calculation, weight version, operator metadata, provenance, and calculation metadata.
  - Produce JSON artifacts (machine-consumable) and PDFs (human-readable) with matching data templates.
  - Sign artifacts using a server-side key (KMS/HSM). Include integrity hashes (e.g., content hash, artifact signature, and per-item payload hashes).
  - Store artifact metadata in an audit-trail table: artifact_id, company_id, window, generated_at, signer_id, signature_hash, retention_policy, download_url(s), and access controls.
  - Enforce access control checks to ensure the requesting user has permission to export the dataset.
  - Support configurable retention window for artifact downloads; purge or archive according to policy.
- Data formats:
  - JSON: schema-stable with versioning, including:
    - artifact_metadata: id, company_id, window_start, window_end, generated_at, signer_id, signature, hash
    - ipi_view_reference: view_id, calculation_inputs, weighting_parameters, weight_version
    - narrative_section: top narratives (id, weight, credibility proxy, contributing_events: [raw_payload_id, timestamp, source])
    - raw_payload_references: [payload_id, source, payload_type, retrieval_url (or embedded if small)]
    - event_list: ordered list of NarrativeEvents with timestamps and references
    - integrity: root_hash, per_item_hashes
  - PDF: human-readable template with:
    - Executive summary: IPI score, direction, window
    - Data provenance: sources, payload references, weight version, operator metadata
    - Narrative breakdown: top 3 narratives with short explanations
    - Event timeline: replay-ready list with timestamps and raw payload view links
    - Calculation inputs: exact vectors used, parameters, and rules
    - Signature block: signer, timestamp, and signature hash
- Formats:
  - JSON: machine-friendly, stable field names, deterministic ordering
  - PDF: print-ready, pagination-friendly, accessible structure (Tagged PDFs if possible)

2) Company View (IPI Detail) Page
- UI responsibilities:
  - Display current IPI score for the selected company within the chosen time window.
  - Show directional change indicator (↑ / ↓) and delta value.
  - Display top 3 contributing narratives with:
    - Narrative name/title
    - Contribution weight and credibility proxy
    - Short explanatory text
  - Provide a timeline (events, signals) for the period.
  - CTA to drill down to "Why did this move?" leading to the Drilldown view.
  - Action: Export Artifacts button(s) to initiate generation of signed artifacts (with user prompts for window and scope if needed).
- Data handling:
  - Ensure all lists are guarded against null/undefined values per runtime safety rules.
  - Use data ?? [] and Array.isArray checks when deriving UI lists (e.g., narratives, events).
  - Initialize state with appropriate defaults: useState<YourType[]>([]) for arrays.
- Accessibility:
  - Keyboard navigable controls, descriptive aria labels, and meaningful button text.
- Visuals:
  - Use card layouts with the project’s design language, including top hero section with IPI score, a compact narrative chips row, and a left-aligned content rhythm.
- Interactions:
  - Hover states for narratives to show quick details; click to open drill-down panel.

3) Drilldown — Why Did This Move?
- UI responsibilities:
  - Detailed explanation for the selected narrative or IPI movement.
  - List underlying NarrativeEvents with:
    - raw payload viewing (preview or full, depending on size)
    - authority signals, credibility signals
    - timestamps
    - replayable chronological view (timeline)
  - Ability to open raw payload in a viewer modal or pane (with copy/download).
  - Option to generate artifacts limited to the selected narrative slice and generation scope.
- Data handling:
  - Guard all arrays and nested structures against nulls/undefineds.
  - Use Array.isArray with fallbacks for rendering event lists and payloads.
- Visuals:
  - Timeline visualization minimalistic: small markers for events, hover tooltips with timestamp and snippet, ability to scrub chronology.
- UX:
  - Lightweight transitions (slide/fade) for the drill-down panel, keep a coherent visual language with the rest of the app.
- Accessibility:
  - Ensure contrast, focus states, and screen reader compatibility.

## Implementation Requirements

### Frontend
- Frameworks: React (TypeScript preferred) with a modern state management approach (e.g., React Query or SWR for data fetching; Zustand or Redux optional).
- Components:
  - AuditArtifactExporterButton: handles artifact generation request, shows status, and handles download links after generation.
  - IPIHeroCard: displays current IPI value, direction, time window.
  - NarrativesBar: renders top 3 narratives with weights and mini-analytics chips.
  - TimelineChart or TimelineList: compact visualization of events; should gracefully handle empty data.
  - DrilldownPanel: collapsible panel that shows narrative event details with raw payload access.
  - RawPayloadViewerModal: in-app viewer for raw payload content (depends on payload size and permissions).
  - PDFPreviewOrDownloadRow: presents generated artifact PDFs for download (with metadata).
- State defaults and safety patterns:
  - Initialize array states as useState<T[]>([]) for any list.
  - When rendering lists, guard: (items ?? []).map(...) or Array.isArray(items) ? items.map(...) : [].
  - When handling API responses, validate shapes: const list = Array.isArray(response?.data) ? response.data : [].
  - Use optional chaining for nested data: obj?.property?.nested.
- Data-fetching:
  - Use robust hooks to fetch company IPI data, narrative events, and calculation inputs. Guard against null results and provide sensible empty-state UI.
- Accessibility and UX:
  - Focus styles consistent with design tokens. Ensure high-contrast interactive elements and keyboard accessibility.
- Security:
  - Ensure export requests pass an authorization check on the client, and server validates permissions before artifact generation.
  - Do not expose raw payloads to unauthorized users; enforce access controls server-side.
- Printing & PDF:
  - Implement a PDF generation path on the backend; provide a download URL in the UI after signing.
  - Consider a preview layout in the UI for the PDF before export if feasible.

### Backend
- Language/stack: Node.js (TypeScript) or your preferred server stack with strong typing.
- Endpoints:
  - POST /api/export/ipI-artifact
    - Body: { companyId, windowStart, windowEnd, viewId, includeNarratives?: string[], format?: 'json' | 'pdf' }
    - Response: { artifactId, status, downloadUrl_json?, downloadUrl_pdf?, signatureHash? }
  - GET /api/export/artifact/:artifactId
    - Permissions checked; serves signed artifact or a public signed URL.
  - POST /api/export/artifact/:artifactId/sign
    - Initiates server-side signing process if needed; returns signature metadata.
- Data models:
  - Artifact
    - id, companyId, windowStart, windowEnd, viewId, weightVersion, calculationInputs, narrativeEvents: [{ id, rawPayloadId, source, timestamp, ... }], payloadReferences: [{ payloadId, type, sourceUrl }], signature, signatureAlgorithm, rootHash, createdAt, status, accessControlList, retentionPolicy
  - RawPayload
    - id, payloadType, payloadData (or reference), source, retrievedAt
  - NarrativeEvent
    - id, narrativeId, source, timestamp, rawPayloadId, credibilitySignals, authoritySignals, metadata
  - CalculationInput
    - vectorName, value
  - Weighting
    - version, parameters
  - AuditTrail
    - artifactId, action, actorId, timestamp
- Signing & integrity:
  - Use KMS/HSM to generate digital signatures for the artifact payload and per-item hashes.
  - Compute a root hash over the JSON payload, and include per-item hashes in the artifact.
  - Store signature metadata and verification data alongside artifact.
- Data integrity:
  - Ensure all arrays are validated; treat missing data as empty arrays.
  - Always coalesce results: data ?? [].
- Security/Authorization:
  - Validate user permissions for company, window, and export scope.
  - Enforce least-privilege; audit all export requests.
- Persistence:
  - Persist artifacts metadata and provide retrievable download references according to retention policy.
- Performance:
  - Index artifact lookups by companyId, window, viewId. Use streaming or chunked serialization for large payloads if needed.
- Validation:
  - Validate request payloads server-side; reject invalid dates, missing required fields; sanitize inputs.

### Integration
- Data flow:
  - Frontend requests export with companyId, window, and view details.
  - Backend fetches necessary NarrativeEvents, raw payloads, and calculation inputs from data sources (IPI engine, narratives store, raw payload store).
  - Backend composes artifact payload, signs, and stores artifact metadata.
  - Backend returns artifactId and secure download URLs; frontend provides them to the user.
- Data contracts:
  - Establish a stable API schema with explicit field names and types.
  - Include versioning in artifact JSON schema; PDF template uses the same version for consistency.
- Error handling:
  - Propagate clear error messages to frontend with proper HTTP status codes (400 for validation, 403/401 for auth, 500 for server errors).
- Observability:
  - Instrument endpoints with metrics: request counts, latency, error rate.
  - Log access attempts for audits, including user, companyId, and window.

## User Experience Flow
1) User logs in and navigates to Company View (IPI Detail).
2) User selects a company and time window (start/end) for the IPI view.
3) The page renders:
   - Current IPI score, direction, and delta.
   - Top 3 narratives with chips and short explanations.
   - Timeline of underlying signals.
   - An “Export Audit Artifacts” CTA.
4) User clicks Export; a modal prompts for scope (which narratives or full view) and confirms formats (JSON, PDF). The system prompts for optional retention window policy if configurable.
5) The frontend sends a secure request to /api/export/ipI-artifact.
6) Backend validates permissions, gathers required data, constructs the artifact payload, signs it, stores artifact metadata, and returns artifactId and signed URLs.
7) The frontend displays status: “Export in progress” or “Export ready.” If ready, show download links for JSON and PDF with signature/authentication indicators.
8) User optionally drills down to Drilldown — Why Did This Move? by selecting a narrative; the Drilldown view renders:
   - Narrative explanation
   - List of NarrativeEvents with timestamps and raw payload references
   - A RawPayloadViewer modal to view or download raw payloads
   - A path to generate a focused artifact including the selected narrative slice
9) Users can re-run exports or view artifact history from an Admin/Export History panel.

